    body: "The Black church has been a second home for Black elders since before emancipation. Within those walls, generations have found prayer partners, choir families, missionary societies, and senior fellowship groups that fill the week with purpose. For a Black senior who is widowed, newly retired, recently moved, or feeling isolated, finding a strong senior ministry can restore a sense of belonging in a way that nothing else can. A Tuesday Bible study, a Wednesday choir rehearsal, a Thursday senior luncheon, and a Sunday morning service together build a rhythm of love and connection.\n\nThe African Methodist Episcopal Church, founded by Bishop Richard Allen in 1816, and the National Baptist Convention USA, founded in 1880, are the two largest historically Black denominations in America. Both have strong traditions of senior ministry. AME churches often run a Senior Missionary Society, a Women's Missionary Society senior chapter, and a Lay Organization with senior chapters. National Baptist churches commonly have a Senior Missionary Department, a Mothers Board, a Deacons Board, and Senior Brotherhood and Sisterhood groups. Other Black Baptist groups like the Progressive National Baptist Convention, the National Baptist Convention of America, and the Full Gospel Baptist Church Fellowship have similar structures.\n\nFinding the right group often means visiting a few churches and asking the right questions. Every congregation has a different feel. One AME church may have 30 active seniors who meet weekly for fellowship and travel. Another may have only a handful. A Baptist church across town may have a thriving Mothers Board that welcomes new members with open arms, or a quieter program that needs new leaders. Visiting in person, even just once, tells you more than any website ever could.\n\nThis guide walks through how to research nearby AME and Baptist churches, how to learn about their senior programs without feeling awkward, and how to introduce yourself in a way that opens doors. We also cover what to expect from a typical senior ministry meeting and how to step into leadership if you feel called. Take your time choosing a church home. The right fellowship group can carry you for years.",
